	        <tr>
			  <td colspan=3 valign="top">
		          <span class=msg>
				   This is an FAQ to help people figure out what their upgrade options are.  Please post your comments and I'll try to work them into the first post (so don't be surprise if your post suddenly disappears; it just means I've integrated it into the FAQ).   <br>  <br> ------------- <br>  <br> <b>How much RAM is enough?</b> <br>  <br> Current Answer: 1 gigabyte.  <br>  <br> Two EQ2 beta players have already commented that Windows XP running EQ2 will cause paging on a 512mb system.  That means dramatic slow-downs at key points, like zoning.  Allegedly the game is playable with 512mb, and that's the minimum system requirement, but if you can expand to 1 gigabyte, we're told, it'll be a lot faster at those key points.  Note that this will not improve your *frame rate* (more on that below), but it should improve your overall computer speed with EQ2, including load times, zoning times, and possibly more. <br>  <br> <b>How do I increase my RAM?</b> <br>  <br> Older systems typically have either SDRAM or DDR RAM (sometimes called &quot;DDRAM&quot;).  DDR is the faster stuff, and if you have that you're in good shape.  If you have an older system with SDRAM, you can realize a *significant* performance boost by replacing your system with a newer one with DDR, even if it runs at the same clock rate.  Consider buying a new computer.   <br>  <br> Both types can be upgraded.  With SDRAM, go straight to the slot parameters discussion below.  For DDR, however, you have one additional consideration:  <br>  <br> - How fast is my DDR RAM?   <br>  <br> DDR is measured in two ways.  The more common way today is the &quot;PC&quot; number, such as &quot;PC2700&quot;, or &quot;PC4400&quot;.  The older way is megahertz, such as &quot;333mhz&quot; or &quot;400mhz&quot;.  The motherboard's RAM paramters are, unfortunately, measured in megahertz, which makes this really confusing, but the reason for the change is that you have some flexibility in terms of RAM speed versus motherboard speed, and you don't necessarily want to match the two.  But this is not really the place for that discussion -- the key here is to match the RAM you're buying with what's already in your system. <br>  <br> <i>If you don't know, you have to replace it.</i>  You don't want to guess, or you could run into some strange problems if they don't match (if it works at all).   <br>  <br>  <br> <b>The general parameters for figuring this out are:</b> <br> - How many slots does my motherboard have?   <br> - How many of those slots are empty? <br>  <br> <i>If all of your slots are full, you're stuck with one option: Replacement.  If you have open slots, AND you know what kind of RAM you currently have, AND you know its speed if it's DDR, then you can buy the same type and expand.  </i> <br>  <br>  <br> <b>Baseline pricing</b> (to figure out if you're paying the right amount) can be established by careful consultation with the Pricewatch web site.  Look for the &quot;memory-system&quot; hyperlink at the top of the third column.  <br>  <br> <a target="_blank" href="http://www.pricewatch.com/">http://www.pricewatch.com/</a> <br>  <br> Once you've established roughly what you SHOULD be paying, you can go to a store and buy it.  Pricewatch has stores listed, but I'd like to collect a list of stores that Grey Hawke members have used, if we can.  Here are some to start us off: <br>  <br> <b>Grey Hawke Approved Stores</b> <br> (Note: That's approved in the general sense that we've used them successfully.  No guarantees are implied!) <br> <a target="_blank" href="http://www.newegg.com/index.asp">NewEgg</a> <br> <a target="_blank" href="http://www.mwave.com/">Multiwave Direct</a> <br> (Please post your favorites below, and I'll add them to this list.) 
